A style of gaming in [[first-person shooters]] (FPS), where realistic ("real-world") settings are simulated by the gaming engine (to the best of its ability) and players use authentic military tactics to accomplish goals in the game.   '''Tactical Realism''' requires enforcement through a combination of in game rules, server settings and often game modificiation.  While most FPS games require some level of modification to provide tactical realistic gameplay, some games, like ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six|Rainbow Six]]'', ''[[Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon|Ghost Recon]]'' and [[Red Orchestra: Ostfront 41-45|Red Orchestra]], are more suited to tactical realistic gameplay without modification.

'''Tactical Realism''' can also describe the manner in which some [[gaming clans]] organize themselves.  These clans adopt the rank, name and insignia of an actual combat unit past or present.

==Tactical Realism Rules==
Game servers enforce and encourage tactical realistic gameplay through rules the players on a server much follow.  Typical rules on a tactical realism game server are (but not limited to):
* No [[bunny hopping]]
* No snaking
* No map exploits like ledging
* No [[run and gun]]
* No [[spam computer game|grenade spam]]
* No In-game map showing locations of friendly players

